[[File:Nala Damayanti.jpg|300px|thumb|[[Nala]]-[[Damayanti]] theme, from the [[Mahabharat]] in Pahari style]] '''Pahari painting''' (literally meaning a painting from the mountainous regions: ''pahar'' means a mountain in [[Hindi]]) is an umbrella term used for a form of [[Indian painting]], done mostly in miniature forms, originating from Himalayan hill kingdoms of North India, during 17th-19th century, notably [[Basohli]], Mankot, [[Nurpur State|Nurpur]], [[Chamba State|Chamba]], [[Kangra State|Kangra]], [[Guler State|Guler]], [[Mandi State|Mandi]], and [[Garhwal Kingdom|Garhwal]].<ref>[http://www.vam.ac.uk/collections/asia/asia_features/sikhism/art/hindu/index.html Hindu Hill Kingdoms] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330034200/http://www.vam.ac.uk/collections/asia/asia_features/sikhism/art/hindu/index.html |date=30 March 2010 }} ''[[V&A Museum]]''.</ref><ref>[http://www.kamat.com/kalranga/art/pahari.htm Pahari] ''Kamat''.</ref> [[Nainsukh]] was a famous master of the mid-18th century, followed by his family workshop for another two generations.
==Origin and area== [[File:Radha celebrating Holi, c1788.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Radha]] celebrating ''[[Holi]]'', ca 1788.]] [[File:Sudama bows at the glimpse of Krishna's golden palace in Dwarka. ca 1775-1790 painting.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Sudama]] bows at the glimpse of Krishna's golden palace in [[Dwarka]]. ca 1775-1790 painting.]]
The Pahari school developed and flourished during 17th-19th centuries stretching from [[Jammu]] to [[Almora]] and [[Garhwal Kingdom|Garhwal]], in the sub-[[Himalayas|Himalayan]] [[India]], through [[Himachal Pradesh]]. Each created stark variations within the genre, ranging from bold intense [[Basohli Painting]], originating from [[Basohli]] in [[Jammu and Kashmir]], to the delicate and lyrical [[Kangra paintings]], which became synonymous to the style before other schools of paintings developed. The Kangra style reached its pinnacle with paintings of [[Works of Jayadeva#Pahari paintings|Radha and Krishna]], inspired by [[Jayadeva|Jayadev]]'s [[Gita Govinda]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=8EGUpX1O0hoC&pg=RA2-PA62&dq=Kangra+painting&as_brr=0 Pahari centres] ''Arts of India: Architecture, Sculpture, Painting, Music, Dance and Handicraft'', by Krishna Chaitanya. Published by Abhinav Publications, 1987. {{ISBN|81-7017-209-8}}. ''Page 62''.</ref>
Pahari painting grew out of the [[Mughal painting]], though this was patronized mostly by the Rajput kings who ruled many parts of the region, and gave birth to a new idiom in Indian painting.<ref>[http://www.culturopedia.com/Painting/pahari.html Pahari]</ref>
==Schools of Pahari painting== * [[Haripur Guler#Guler Paintings|Guler School]] * [[Kangra paintings|Kangra School]] * [[Basohli Painting|Basohli School]] * [[Chamba, Himachal Pradesh#Chamba miniature paintings|Chamba School]] <ref>[http://www.culturenorthindia.com/hp/fine_arts.htm Pahari Paintings] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022043908/http://culturenorthindia.com/hp/fine_arts.htm |date=22 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.dalhousie.net/paharipaintings.htm Pahari paintings]</ref> * [[Garhwal Division|Garhwal]] School
